	<h2>Wood Fencing: The Classic Choice</h2>

	<h3>Types of Wood Fencing</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Cedar:</strong> Naturally rot-resistant, beautiful grain, premium pricing</li>
		<li><strong>Redwood:</strong> Similar benefits to cedar, California-sourced</li>
		<li><strong>Pressure-treated pine:</strong> Budget-friendly, requires more maintenance</li>
		<li><strong>Douglas fir:</strong> Strong and durable, mid-range option</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Advantages of Wood</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Privacy:</strong> Solid wood panels provide complete visual screening</li>
		<li><strong>Customization:</strong> Can be stained or painted any color; endless style options</li>
		<li><strong>Natural aesthetic:</strong> Warm, organic appearance that many homeowners love</li>
		<li><strong>Lower upfront cost:</strong> Generally less expensive initially than metal</li>
		<li><strong>Easy repairs:</strong> Individual boards can be replaced affordably</li>
		<li><strong>DIY-friendly:</strong> Easier for skilled homeowners to install</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Disadvantages of Wood</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Maintenance required:</strong> Needs staining/sealing every 2-3 years</li>
		<li><strong>Shorter lifespan:</strong> 15-20 years typical, even with maintenance</li>
		<li><strong>Weather vulnerability:</strong> Can warp, crack, or rot over time</li>
		<li><strong>Pest susceptibility:</strong> Termites and wood-boring insects</li>
		<li><strong>Fire risk:</strong> Burns in wildfires (relevant in some Stockton areas)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Wood Performance in Stockton Climate</h3>
	<p>Stockton's hot, dry summers and mild winters present specific challenges:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Heat causes wood to dry and crack</li>
		<li>UV exposure accelerates deterioration without protection</li>
		<li>Relatively low humidity is actually favorable for wood</li>
		<li>Irrigation overspray can cause localized rot</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Metal Fencing: The Durable Alternative</h2>

	<h3>Types of Metal Fencing</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Aluminum:</strong> Lightweight, rust-proof, most common residential choice</li>
		<li><strong>Wrought iron:</strong> Traditional, extremely strong, heavier and pricier</li>
		<li><strong>Steel:</strong> Industrial strength, various coating options</li>
		<li><strong>Chain link:</strong> Budget metal option (not covered in this comparison)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Advantages of Metal</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Exceptional durability:</strong> Lasts 30-50+ years with minimal degradation</li>
		<li><strong>Low maintenance:</strong> Occasional cleaning is typically all that's needed</li>
		<li><strong>Security:</strong> Strong deterrent; difficult to breach</li>
		<li><strong>Pest-proof:</strong> No termites or wood-boring insects</li>
		<li><strong>Fire-resistant:</strong> Won't burn in wildfires</li>
		<li><strong>Elegant appearance:</strong> Classic, upscale aesthetic</li>
		<li><strong>Property value:</strong> Often increases home value more than wood</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Disadvantages of Metal</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>No privacy:</strong> Traditional designs allow visibility through fence</li>
		<li><strong>Higher initial cost:</strong> Premium pricing compared to basic wood</li>
		<li><strong>Heat absorption:</strong> Metal gets hot in Stockton summers (pet/child concern)</li>
		<li><strong>Limited customization:</strong> Colors determined by manufacturer</li>
		<li><strong>Rust potential:</strong> Iron and steel can rust without proper coating</li>
		<li><strong>Harder repairs:</strong> Damage repair can be more complex</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Metal Performance in Stockton Climate</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Aluminum performs excellently—no rust, handles heat well</li>
		<li>Iron/steel need quality powder coating to prevent rust</li>
		<li>Heat absorption is real concern—dark metal in summer sun can burn</li>
		<li>No concerns about humidity or wood-related deterioration</li>
	</ul>

