				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$19,300</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$7,300</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>

	<p><strong>Key insight:</strong> While wood costs less upfront, metal often costs less over the fence's lifetime due to lower maintenance and longer lifespan.</p>

	<h2>Aesthetic Considerations</h2>

	<h3>Home Style Matching</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Traditional/Colonial homes:</strong> Both work well; wrought iron is classic</li>
		<li><strong>Ranch style:</strong> Wood fencing is traditional choice</li>
		<li><strong>Modern/Contemporary:</strong> Either can work; depends on design</li>
		<li><strong>Mediterranean:</strong> Iron/metal complements beautifully</li>
		<li><strong>Farmhouse:</strong> Wood is the natural choice</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Curb Appeal Impact</h3>
	<p>Both materials can significantly enhance or detract from curb appeal depending on condition and style selection. Well-maintained wood looks beautiful; neglected wood looks shabby. Metal maintains appearance with less effort.</p>

	<h2>Security Comparison</h2>

	<h3>Physical Security</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Metal:</strong> Extremely difficult to cut, climb, or break through</li>
		<li><strong>Wood:</strong> Can be cut with tools, kicked through if weakened</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Visual Deterrent</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Metal:</strong> Appears formidable; deters casual intruders</li>
		<li><strong>Wood:</strong> Solid privacy can actually aid intruders once breached</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Privacy Considerations</h2>

	<h3>If Privacy Is Priority</h3>
	<p>Wood is the clear winner for privacy. Standard metal fencing allows visibility through pickets. However, metal fencing can be combined with privacy solutions:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Hedge plantings behind metal fence</li>
		<li>Privacy screen panels attached to metal framework</li>
		<li>Metal panels with solid backing (specialty products)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Making Your Decision</h2>

	<h3>Choose Wood If:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Privacy is your primary concern</li>
		<li>You prefer warm, natural aesthetics</li>
		<li>Initial budget is limited</li>
		<li>You enjoy DIY maintenance projects</li>
		<li>You want maximum customization (colors, styles)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Choose Metal If:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>You want minimal long-term maintenance</li>
		<li>Security is a priority</li>
		<li>You're thinking long-term investment</li>
		<li>You prefer classic, elegant appearance</li>
		<li>You have a pool (often required for safety)</li>
		<li>Fire resistance matters in your area</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Conclusion</h2>
	<p>Neither wood nor metal is universally "better"—the right choice depends on your priorities. Wood offers unmatched privacy and natural beauty at a lower upfront cost, while metal delivers superior durability, security, and long-term value. Many Stockton homeowners use both: metal in front yards for curb appeal and security, wood in backyards for privacy.</p>

	<p>Consider your specific needs, maintenance willingness, and budget over the fence's entire lifespan—not just installation cost. Both materials can serve you well for years when properly installed and maintained.</p>

	<p>Need help deciding? Contact us for a consultation where we can assess your property and discuss which material best meets your needs.</p>

